{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa4713a3-ff5d-472e-a899-4c65686efd62","content":"Use **`dotnet-trace`** — it's the lowest-friction option for containers:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID (usually 1)\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (default provider includes CPU sampling)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (use `--format speedscope` for browser-based viewing).\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- If `dotnet tool install` isn't viable (read-only filesystem), use the **global tool sidecar** approach or download the standalone `dotnet-trace` binary\n- For deeper OS-level analysis, `dotnet-trace` also supports `--format speedscope` which doesn't require Windows tooling\n\n**Alternative — `perf` + BPF** (if you need OS-level detail):\n```bash\n# Requires SYS_ADMIN / privileged container\nperf record -g -p <PID> -- sleep 30\nperf script > out.perf\n```\n\nFor most .NET CPU investigations, **`dotnet-trace` with `cpu-sampling`** is the recommended starting point.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8f160be1-da63-473b-8345-97c8eabf6dfd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":427,"requestId":"2C45:A64D3:2813F84:2C652E8:69F94761"},"id":"d7feec47-7ab6-441e-8f21-4e93816ee7af","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:27:09.355Z","parentId":"c36cfa08-b1ee-40bf-b2ab-091187bcbc05"}
